   {:e #blake3 "b874e9062f62bb4745918166871c2a19fcf686279b2cf62a11fb874a110bc5d0" :a :harvest/accomplishments :v "Session entity: :task/t-7d24381f; Session entity: :session/s-1774488787\nThe drift package (internal/drift/) implements a bilateral drift analysis system measuring divergence between spec and implementation. It classifies drift along three dimensions: Direction (impl-ahead, spec-ahead, contradictory, mutual), Severity (additive, contradictory, structural), and Intentionality (planned, accidental, organic). It further decomposes into ImplDrift (unspecified code, unimplemented specs, contradictions) and IntentDrift (uncovered non-negotiables, purposeless elements). A unique ProcessDriftInfo struct measures methodology compliance via spec_first_ratio, tool_intermediation, witness_coverage, and validate_gating. The QualityBreakdown into correctness/depth/coherence directly maps to braid's F(S) boundary decomposition.; ARCHITECTURAL: 12 of 38 packages (32%) have zero test files: bundle, cascade, diff, exemplar, impact, implorder, oplog, progress, query, renderer, skeleton, state. Meanwhile 403 ddis:implements/ddis:maintains annotations span 126 files — the codebase self-tracks spec compliance through comments but does not mechanically verify many of these claims. The witness system (APP-ADR-030) exists precisely to close this gap, but the packages responsible for key functionality like cascade analysis, impact assessment, and implementation ordering have no tests at all. The CLI package has 53 source files but only 1 test file — the test-to-source ratio is 0.02, suggesting the CLI layer is almost entirely untested. This matches the classic Go CLI anti-pattern where Cobra command setup code is hard to test.; The events package (internal/events/) implements three-stream event sourcing (APP-ADR-015). Stream 1 is discovery (ideas, questions, decisions), Stream 2 is specification (parse, validate, drift), Stream 3 is implementation (issues, status, findings). Events are JSONL-appended with SHA-256 content hashing, causal predecessor tracking (Causes []string), and schema versioning. The Event struct uses json.RawMessage for the payload — heterogeneous payloads under a uniform envelope. This is close to braid's append-only datom concept but without CRDT merge semantics.; The witness package (internal/witness/) implements a graduated evidence system for invariant verification (APP-ADR-030). Evidence types form a lattice: test < annotation < scan < review < attestation. The system supports mechanical verification (--verify: require code annotations with ddis:implements/ddis:maintains tags), and Gestalt-Theory-framed review bundles (--review-context: compile invariant + code locations + review criteria into a single document for Level 4 human review). WitnessSummary tracks total invariants, witnessed count, coverage ratio, and stale witnesses (invalidated by code changes via content hash mismatch). Auto-invalidation (APP-INV-041) means witnesses expire when the code they reference changes — exactly the calibration feedback loop braid models with its hypothesis ledger.; The causal package (internal/causal/) implements a causal DAG over the event stream. Events form a directed acyclic graph where each event lists its causal predecessors via the Causes field. The DAG supports reachability queries, independence detection (two events with no causal path = concurrent), provenance tracing (element-ID to originating events), and semilattice merge for CRDT convergence (APP-INV-081, APP-ADR-063). This is the Go CLI's version of what braid calls frontier comparison and CRDT merge — but operating at the event level rather than the datom level. The merge function computes set union of independent events, matching braid's C4 constraint exactly.; ARCHITECTURAL: There are two confusingly named packages — discover (internal/discover/) and discovery (internal/discovery/) — that handle overlapping but distinct concerns. The discover package implements cognitive mode classification (divergent/convergent/incubation) from event streams with DoF (degrees-of-freedom) hints, thread management, and context assembly. The discovery package implements artifact map reduction from JSONL streams, task derivation, and thread state management. Both deal with discovery events, both have thread concepts, both import events models. The naming collision (discover vs discovery) signals an incomplete refactoring or organic growth without architectural review. A unified package with clear sub-concerns would reduce confusion. The materialize package (4 files, 3 tests) is similar — it overlaps conceptually with projector (1 file) which renders materialized views.; The storage package (internal/storage/) implements a 30-table normalized SQLite schema (APP-ADR-005). The schema covers spec_index, source_files, sections, invariants, ADRs, negative_cases, gates, glossary, examples, xrefs, and more. Every table uses integer PKs with REFERENCES for foreign keys. Content hashing (SHA-256) is pervasive — every entity has a content_hash column for deterministic identity. The models.go file mirrors each table as a Go struct. This is a classic relational approach — the opposite of braid's EAV datom model.; The consistency package implements a 5-tier contradiction detection engine: Tier 2 (graph-based: typed edges, governance overlap, cycles), Tier 3 (SAT via gophersat: semi-formal to propositional encoding), Tier 4 (heuristic: polarity/quantifier/numeric + LSI), Tier 5 (SMT via Z3 subprocess), Tier 6 (LLM-as-judge via Anthropic API). Each tier has its own file (graph.go, sat.go, heuristic.go, smt.go, llm.go). The Contradiction struct carries confidence scores and resolution hints. ConflictTypes include governance_overlap, polarity_inversion, quantifier_conflict, numeric_bound_conflict, circular_implication, sat_unsatisfiable, smt_unsatisfiable, semantic_tension. This is the most architecturally sophisticated package — a graduated verification pipeline from cheap/fast to expensive/thorough.; ARCHITECTURAL: The storage package is a critical coupling hub — imported by 83 other files across the codebase, nearly every non-trivial package depends on it. The events package is second at 30 imports. This creates a strong architectural bottleneck: any change to storage/models.go or storage/queries.go cascades across almost every package. The storage package also passes raw *sql.DB pointers everywhere rather than using interfaces, making it impossible to test packages independently without a real SQLite database. This tight coupling to concrete SQL types is the single largest architectural weakness — it prevents unit testing without integration infrastructure and makes the transition to any other storage backend (like braid's datom store) a total rewrite rather than an adapter swap.; The parser package (internal/parser/) is the largest and most structured package with 21 Go files. It parses DDIS specifications from both monolith and modular YAML manifests (APP-ADR-010). The manifest.yaml struct encodes: ddis_version, tier_mode, parent_spec hierarchy, context_budget (with reasoning_reserve), constitution (system+domain), module declarations with cross-references (maintains, interfaces, implements, adjacent), and an invariant_registry. Each ontological element type (invariant, ADR, negative_case, gate, glossary, example, xref, whynot, performance, verification) has its own dedicated parser file — 11 element types total. The parser is the gateway to the entire DDIS data model." :op :assert}
